{"ClientSettings":{"Pn":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"P"},"Sc":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"H"},"Qz":{"Cn":1,"St":0,"Qs":0,"Prod":"T"},"Ap":true,"Mute":true,"Lad":"2026-03-16T00:00:00Z","Iotd":0,"Gwb":0,"Tns":0,"Dft":null,"Mvs":0,"Flt":0,"Imp":1,"Tobn":0},"MediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"If Rio de Janeiro were a story, today's image would be one of its most iconic chapters. It captures the essence of a metropolis founded on 1 March 1565 to protect Guanabara Bay and control the trade of brazilwood. Since then, it has evolved from a military settlement into a cultural centre, from a strategic port into a national symbol. The city has faced invasions, fires and major political shifts, yet has repeatedly turned challenges into urban expression. Today, the capital of the state of Rio de Janeiro is among the most recognisable cityscapes in the world.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.AnivRio_ROW3862828341_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.AnivRio_ROW3862828341_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Cable car and Sugarloaf Mountain, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil","Copyright":"© f11photo/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260316_AnivRio\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Sugarloaf+Mountain&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260316_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260316_AnivRio"},"Ssd":"20260316","Name":"AnivRio","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3862828341","FullDateString":"Mar 16, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Spring break on Vancouver Island, Canada looks a little different. In Canada, people can witness the annual spring migration of thousands of grey whales as they pass close to the island's west coast. Created by local communities in the 1980s, the Pacific Rim Whale Festival marks the whales' return north from breeding lagoons in Baja California, Mexico.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PacificRimNP_ROW9181043528_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PacificRimNP_ROW9181043528_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Pacific Rim National Park Reserve, Vancouver Island, Canada","Copyright":"© EmilyNorton/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260315_PacificRimNP\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Pacific+Rim+National+Park+Reserve&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260315_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260315_PacificRimNP"},"Ssd":"20260315","Name":"PacificRimNP","Market":"ROW","Hash":"9181043528","FullDateString":"Mar 15, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Time has altered the land around it, but Lanyon Quoit in Cornwall, England, still commands attention. Built in the Neolithic period, 'The Giant's Table' offers a rare chance to consider how early settlers marked their presence. Formed by upright stones holding a massive capstone of about 13,000 kilograms, the monument likely served as a communal burial chamber.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.CornwallDolmen_ROW3459140266_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.CornwallDolmen_ROW3459140266_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Lanyon Quoit, a Neolithic dolmen in Cornwall, England","Copyright":"© Helen Hotson/Alamy","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260314_CornwallDolmen\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Lanyon+Quoit&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260314_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260314_CornwallDolmen"},"Ssd":"20260314","Name":"CornwallDolmen","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3459140266","FullDateString":"Mar 14, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Silence on the water often means something special is happening—have you noticed how swans seem to turn lakes into slow-moving classrooms? A mute swan glides across calm water with its cygnets in Hesse, Germany. This scene is common across European lakes and river landscapes, from Lake Constance and the Mecklenburg Lake District to restored river channels in many towns and cities. These waterways provide sheltered shorelines and abundant aquatic plants, the swan's primary food source.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SwanHesse_ROW3213322861_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SwanHesse_ROW3213322861_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Mute swan with chicks, Hesse, Germany","Copyright":"© Wilfried Martin/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260313_SwanHesse\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Mute+swan&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260313_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260313_SwanHesse"},"Ssd":"20260313","Name":"SwanHesse","Market":"ROW","Hash":"3213322861","FullDateString":"Mar 13, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"High in Ecuador's cloud forests, a young sunbittern spreads its wings in an early display, casting flashes of orange, black and white through the filtered green light. The sudden contrast cuts through the moss‑covered branches and leaf‑shadowed understorey, offering a snapshot of the species' dramatic wing patterns. Adult sunbitterns most often show these bold markings during defensive displays, briefly transforming an elusive bird into a striking spectacle.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SunbitternEcuador_ROW2999974301_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SunbitternEcuador_ROW2999974301_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Juvenile sunbittern displaying at nest, Ecuador","Copyright":"© Andy Rouse/naturepl.com","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260312_SunbitternEcuador\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Sunbittern+bird&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260312_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260312_SunbitternEcuador"},"Ssd":"20260312","Name":"SunbitternEcuador","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2999974301","FullDateString":"Mar 12, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Spring hits differently in Cieza. It doesn't gently unfold—it erupts with colour. Between February and March, this small city in Spain's Murcia region is the epicentre of 'La Floración,' the flowering of peach trees. In a matter of days, more than 4,850 hectares—Spain's largest municipal peach production—transform into a sea of colour we see in today's image.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PeachBloom_ROW2817467939_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PeachBloom_ROW2817467939_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Peach trees in bloom, Cieza, Murcia, Spain","Copyright":"© Juan Maria Coy Vergara/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260311_PeachBloom\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Cieza+Spain&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260311_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260311_PeachBloom"},"Ssd":"20260311","Name":"PeachBloom","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2817467939","FullDateString":"Mar 11, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Have you ever wondered what happens when fire, ice and time negotiate the same territory? Iceland's Hveravellir geothermal field has the answer. In this highland hotspot, energy from the Earth's interior meets the icy surface, triggering a volatile dialogue between pressure, temperature and stone. Fumaroles hiss, steam curls into the air and the ground paints itself with sulphur whites, rust reds and ochre yellows—not only artistry, but chemical reactions driven by extreme heat. In today's image, Bláhver, a natural hot spring, dazzles in electric blue. Its colour comes from mineral- and silica-rich waters that reflect light on the surface.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SpringIceland_ROW2538267892_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SpringIceland_ROW2538267892_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Geothermal blue pool Bláhver at Hveravellir, Iceland","Copyright":"© Juan Maria Coy Vergara/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260310_SpringIceland\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Blahver+pool+Iceland&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260310_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260310_SpringIceland"},"Ssd":"20260310","Name":"SpringIceland","Market":"ROW","Hash":"2538267892","FullDateString":"Mar 10, jjjj"}],"PreloadMediaContents":[{"ImageContent":{"Description":"The strength of nature is nowhere more evident than in powerful storms. Scary? Yes. Fascinating? Even more so. Learning to understand and respect these forces is how people learn to live alongside them. The image of lightning over saguaro cacti captures that balance perfectly. The Sonoran Desert, spanning 260,000 square kilometres across the United States and Mexico, may appear dry and still, but it hosts one of North America's most dynamic desert climates.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SonoranStorm_ROW1923244200_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SonoranStorm_ROW1923244200_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Lightning storm over saguaro cacti, Sonoran Desert, Arizona, United States","Copyright":"© Jack Dykinga/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260323_SonoranStorm\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Sonoran+Desert+Arizona&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260323_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260323_SonoranStorm"},"Ssd":"20260323","Name":"SonoranStorm","Market":"ROW","Hash":"1923244200","FullDateString":"Mar 23, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Water has always shaped human survival, but moments come when simply flowing along is no longer enough—we have to protect the systems that carry us forward. Few places capture that urgency like Lake Tanganyika, set deep within the Great Rift Valley of eastern Africa. Seen from space, it stretches like a narrow ribbon about 676 kilometres long, linking Tanzania, Burundi, the Democratic Republic of the Congo and Zambia. At the shoreline, it's a 10-million-year-old rift basin, formed as the Earth's crust slowly pulled apart.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.TanganyikaWater_ROW4763595612_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.TanganyikaWater_ROW4763595612_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Lake Tanganyika, Africa","Copyright":"© BEST-BACKGROUNDS/NASA/Shutterstock","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260322_TanganyikaWater\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Lake+Tanganyika&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260322_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260322_TanganyikaWater"},"Ssd":"20260322","Name":"TanganyikaWater","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4763595612","FullDateString":"Mar 22, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"If Earth ran on routine check-ups, wetlands like the Danube Delta, shared between Romania and Ukraine, would top the list. This vast landscape quietly filters water, absorbs floodwaters and shelters wildlife on a remarkable scale. Covering more than 5,800 square kilometres, the Danube Delta Biosphere Reserve is one of Europe's largest and best-preserved wetlands. It's where the Danube River finally slows down, splitting into channels, lakes, reed beds and marshes before meeting the Black Sea. Letea Forest, featured in today's image, is a part of this vast biosphere.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.LeteaForest_ROW4397618654_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.LeteaForest_ROW4397618654_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Letea Forest, Danube Delta, Romania","Copyright":"© Wild Wonders of Europe/Widstrand/Nature Picture Library","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260321_LeteaForest\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Danube+Delta&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260321_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260321_LeteaForest"},"Ssd":"20260321","Name":"LeteaForest","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4397618654","FullDateString":"Mar 21, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"A white snowdrop feels like spring's quiet debut. No fanfare, no fuss—just a small flower daring to appear as the season begins to turn. Snowdrops are among the earliest bloomers, often pushing through frozen soil, leaf litter and even light snow. How do they manage it? Their nodding, bell-shaped flowers protect pollen from cold rain, while antifreeze-like compounds in their cells help them tolerate frost. Delicate-looking, yes. Fragile? Not at all.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.SpringSnowdrops_ROW7920205293_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.SpringSnowdrops_ROW7920205293_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Snowdrops in spring","Copyright":"© klagyivik/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260320_SpringSnowdrops\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Galanthus+flower&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260320_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260320_SpringSnowdrops"},"Ssd":"20260320","Name":"SpringSnowdrops","Market":"ROW","Hash":"7920205293","FullDateString":"Mar 20, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"An egg-laying mammal. No teeth. Reptilian gait. Built-in body armour. If the short-beaked echidna sounds like a checklist of contradictions, that's because it is—and it owns it. Native to Australia, Tasmania and parts of New Guinea, it's one of the few surviving monotremes, or mammals that lay eggs. Despite the headlines, it still qualifies as a mammal: it has fur, produces milk and is warm-blooded. The twist? Milk is released through specialised skin patches rather than nipples, leaving the young to lap it up.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.EchidnaAustralia_ROW4548583116_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.EchidnaAustralia_ROW4548583116_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Short-beaked echidna, Adelaide Hills, Australia","Copyright":"© Etienne Littlefair/naturepl.com","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260319_EchidnaAustralia\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Short-beaked+echidna&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260319_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260319_EchidnaAustralia"},"Ssd":"20260319","Name":"EchidnaAustralia","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4548583116","FullDateString":"Mar 19, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Tom McCall Waterfront Park, a 12.5-hectare urban oasis along the Willamette River in Portland, Oregon, is one of the city's most beloved green spaces. Each spring—typically from mid-March to early April—it transforms into a sea of soft pink and white as cherry blossoms bloom. These vibrant trees along scenic walking paths offer a peaceful escape in the heart of the city. The park also features notable landmarks like Salmon Street Springs, an interactive fountain with numerous water jets, and the Portland Saturday Market, a favourite local destination.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.PortlandBlossoms_ROW4378783991_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.PortlandBlossoms_ROW4378783991_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Cherry blossoms at Tom McCall Waterfront Park, Portland, Oregon, USA","Copyright":"© Eric Vogt/Tandem Stills + Motion","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260318_PortlandBlossoms\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Tom+McCall+Waterfront+Park&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260318_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260318_PortlandBlossoms"},"Ssd":"20260318","Name":"PortlandBlossoms","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4378783991","FullDateString":"Mar 18, jjjj"},{"ImageContent":{"Description":"Today, we find ourselves in County Donegal in the northwest of Ireland. Grianan of Aileach, a stone ringfort—dating from the Iron Age to the early Middle Ages—linked to the Kings of Aileach and the Northern Uí Néill, stands here. The fort crowns Greenan Mountain and served as a ceremonial and strategic stronghold. Archaeological evidence suggests the site had importance long before the current walls rose in the 6th or 7th century.","Image":{"Url":"/th?id=OHR.DonegalFort_ROW4126307625_1920x1080.webp","Wallpaper":"/th?id=OHR.DonegalFort_ROW4126307625_1920x1200.jpg&rf=LaDigue_1920x1200.jpg","Downloadable":true},"Headline":"Info","Title":"Grianan of Aileach ring fort, Donegal, Ireland","Copyright":"© Lukassek/Getty Images","SocialGood":null,"MapLink":{"Url":"","Link":""},"QuickFact":{"MainText":"","LinkUrl":"","LinkText":""},"TriviaUrl":"/search?q=Bing+homepage+quiz&filters=WQOskey:\"HPQuiz_20260317_DonegalFort\"&FORM=HPQUIZ","BackstageUrl":"/search?q=Grianan+of+Aileach+ring+fort+Donegal&form=hpcapt&filters=HpDate:\"20260317_0700\"+mgzv3configlist:\"BingQA_Encyclopedia_Layout\"","TriviaId":"HPQuiz_20260317_DonegalFort"},"Ssd":"20260317","Name":"DonegalFort","Market":"ROW","Hash":"4126307625","FullDateString":"Mar 17, jjjj"}],"LocStrings":{"LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD":"Beeld van die dag","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_IOTD_LEARN_MORE":"Kom meer te wete","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_DONATE_NOW":"Skenk nou","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_FACT":"Kitsfeit:","LOC_HOMEPAGE_GALLERY_CARD_TITLE":"Onlangse tuisbladbeelde","LOC_HOMEPAGE_VERTICAL_SCROLL_GALLERY_IMAGE_ARIALABEL":"Tuisbladbeeld vir {0}","LOC_HOMEPAGE_ON_THIS_DAY_TITLE":"Op hierdie dag in geskiedenis","LOC_HOMEPAGE_ON_THIS_DAY_IMAGE_ARIALABEL":"Op hierdie dag in {0}, {1}","LOC_HOMEPAGE_SHARE_TOOLTIP":"Deel vandag se Bing-tuisblad","LOC_HOMEPAGE_WALLPAPERDOWNLOAD_TOOLTIP":"Laai hierdie beeld af. Hierdie beeld kan slegs as muurpapier gebruik word.","LOC_MUSCARD_DOWNLOAD_LINK":"Laai hierdie beeld af","LOC_HOMEPAGE_WALLPAPERNOTAVAILABLE":"Hierdie beeld kan nie as muurpapier afgelaai word nie.","LOC_HOMEPAGE_INFO_TEXT":"Inligting","LOC_BING_WP_APP_LINK":"https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2127455","LOC_BING_WP_APP_LINK_TEXT":"Kry die Bing-muurpapiertoepassing","LOC_BING_APP_TEXT":"Kry Bing-muurpapier op jou toestelle","LOC_BING_APP_LINK_PC":"https://bing.microsoftapp.net/bing/?adjust=nk9xri2_dzfz5n2","LOC_BING_APP_LINK_MOBILE":"https:/